'''Aerolux Light Corporation''' was a manufacturer of artful gas-discharge light bulbs from the 1930s through the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Gift Show Opens With 500 Exhibits |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1938/02/22/archives/gift-show-opens-with-500-exhibits-concern-shown-over-world-affairs.html |quote=... opening of the seventeenth semi-annual New York Gift Show at the Hotel Pennsylvania yesterday. ... The Aerolux Light Corporation introduced electric light bulbs which contain figures, such as Mickey Mouse, pink elephants, flowers, etc., within the bulb ... |work=[[New York Times]] |date=February 22, 1938 |accessdate=2010-11-15 }}</ref> Aerolux made these bulbs in a factory in [[New York City]]. US Patents dating back to the 1930s describe the design and construction of these bulbs. <ref>[http://patimg1.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=01989041&homeurl=http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=01989041&OS=PN/01989041&RS=PN/01989041&PageNum=&Rtype=&SectionNum=&idkey=NONE&Input=View+first+page USPTO: 1,989,041 Philip J. Kayatt] (1935)</ref> <ref>[http://patimg1.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=02075744&homeurl=http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=02075744&OS=PN/02075744&RS=PN/02075744&PageNum=&Rtype=&SectionNum=&idkey=NONE&Input=View+first+page USPTO: 2,075,744 Somenosuke Muramatsu]</ref> <ref>[http://patimg1.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=02240334&homeurl=http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=02240334&OS=PN/02240334&RS=PN/02240334&PageNum=&Rtype=&SectionNum=&idkey=NONE&Input=View+first+page USPTO: 2,240,334 Philip J. Kayatt]</ref> <ref>[http://patimg1.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=02263093&homeurl=http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=02263093&OS=PN/02263093&RS=PN/02263093&PageNum=&Rtype=&SectionNum=&idkey=NONE&Input=View+first+page USPTO: 2,263,093 Philip J. Kayatt]</ref> <ref>[http://patimg1.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=03238408&homeurl=http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=03238408&OS=PN/03238408&RS=PN/03238408&PageNum=&Rtype=&SectionNum=&idkey=NONE&Input=View+first+page USPTO: 3,238,408 Philip J. Kayatt]</ref> <ref>[http://patimg1.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=03435286&homeurl=http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=03435286&OS=PN/03435286&RS=PN/03435286&PageNum=&Rtype=&SectionNum=&idkey=NONE&Input=View+first+page USPTO: 3,435,286 Philip J. Kayatt]</ref> Philip J. Kayatt (1896–1975)<!--He was born in Syria. His birth year is different in every document he filled out and ranges from 1892 to 1898. I will use SSDI as canonical --> was president of the company.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reif |first=Rita |coauthors= |title=Neon-The Industrial Craft That's Been Turned Into Decorative Lighting |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A15F9395C1A7A93C3AA178ED85F478785F9 |quote=Mr. Kayatt, the 74-year-old president of the Aerolux Light Company here, may well be one of the few craftsmen still working in neon who devised some of the original neons for the Great White Way in the early nineteen‐twenties. |work=[[New York Times]] |date=May 31, 1973 |accessdate=2010-11-15 }}</ref>
== Description == Aerolux gas discharge light bulbs contained low pressure gas, either neon or argon, or a mixture of the two. Also within the bulb were metal sculptures coated with phosphors. These phosphors fluoresced when excited by [[glow discharge]]. Because glow discharge occurs readily at 110-120 [[volt]]s AC, one could use these bulbs in standard household lamps in the United States.
The phosphors used in the bulbs were somewhat brittle, necessitating care in handling. Shaking or jarring the bulbs would cause flaking and migration of the phosphors to other parts of the metallic sculpture. Such handling would leave non-fluorescing portions of the sculpture and/or migration of phosphors to other surfaces within the bulb.
Aerolux bulbs consumed about 3-5 watts of power. The bulbs had high yield of light produced versus electricity consumed, generally in the range of 50-60 [[Lumen (unit)|lumen]]s/[[watt]], compared to 12-18 lumens/watt for a [[Incandescent light bulb|tungsten filament incandescent bulb]]. <ref>[http://www.ccri.edu/physics/keefe/light.htm The Nature of Light, T.J. Keefe] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612000000/http://www.ccri.edu/physics/keefe/light.htm |date=June 12, 2010 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=May 2017}}
