{{about|the hypothetical dark matter galaxy|other uses|Galaxy X (disambiguation)}}
{{sky|16|21|32.89283|-|51|25|24.1005|300000000}} '''Galaxy X'''<ref name=NatGeo-2011-01-14>{{cite news |url= http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2011/01/110114-galaxy-x-space-dark-matter-dwarf-satellite-science-chakrabarti/ |title= Dark-Matter Galaxy Detected: Hidden Dwarf Lurks Nearby? |date= 14 January 2011 |publisher= National Geographic |author= Richard A. Lovett }}</ref><ref name=PopSci-2011-01-13/> is a postulated [[dark galaxy|dark]] [[satellite galaxy|satellite]] [[dwarf galaxy|dwarf]] [[galaxy]] of the [[Milky Way Galaxy]]. If it exists, it would be composed mostly of [[dark matter]] and [[interstellar gas]] with few [[star]]s.<ref name=NatGeo-2011-01-14/><ref name=ScienceDaily-2015-02-06/> Its proposed location is some {{convert|90|kpc|kly|abbr=on|lk=on}} from the Sun,<ref name=NatGeo-2011-01-14/><ref name=ScienceDaily-2015-02-06/><ref name=2015arXiv150201358C/> behind the disk of the Milky Way,<ref name=NatGeo-2011-01-14/> and some {{convert|12|kpc|kly|abbr=on}} in extent.<ref name=2015arXiv150201358C/> [[Galactic coordinates]] would be (l= -27.4°,b=-1.08°).<ref name=2015arXiv150201358C/>
==Discovery== Observational evidence for this galaxy was presented in 2015,<ref name=NBC-2015-02-06>{{cite news |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/science/space/dark-matter-hunters-suspect-theyve-found-galaxy-x-n301956 |title= Dark Matter Hunters Suspect They've Found 'Galaxy X' |author= Alan Boyle |date= 6 February 2015 |publisher= [[NBC News]] }}</ref> based on the claimed discovery of four, [[Cepheid variable star]]s by Sukanya Chakrabarti [[Rochester Institute of Technology|(RIT)]] and collaborators.<ref name=2015arXiv150201358C/> Search for the stars was motivated by an earlier study <ref name=TechTimes-2015-02-08>{{cite news |url= http://www.techtimes.com/articles/31643/20150208/mysterious-galaxy-x-found-finally-dark-matter-hunters-would-like-to-believe-so.htm |title= Mysterious Galaxy X Found Finally? Dark Matter Hunters Would Like To Believe So |date= 8 February 2015 |publisher= Tech Times }}</ref> that linked a warp in the HI (atomic hydrogen) disk of the Milky Way Galaxy to the tidal effects of a perturbing galaxy.<ref name=ScienceDaily-2015-02-06>{{cite news |url= https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2015/02/150206125346.htm |title= Lifting the veil on a dark galaxy |date= 6 February 2015 |publisher= [[Science Daily]] }}</ref><ref name=2009MNRAS.399L.118C/> The unseen perturber's mass was calculated to be about 1%<ref group=NB>approximately 10 billion [[solar mass]]es</ref> of that of the Milky Way,<ref name=2011ApJ...731...40C/> which would make it the third heaviest satellite of the Milky Way, after the [[Magellanic Clouds]] ([[Large Magellanic Cloud]] and [[Small Magellanic Cloud]], each some 10x larger than Galaxy X).<ref name=NatGeo-2011-01-14/> In this hypothetical model, the putative satellite galaxy would have interacted with the Milky Way some 600 million years ago, coming as close as {{convert|5|-|10|kpc|kly|abbr=on}}, and would now be moving away from the Milky Way.<ref name=2015arXiv150201358C/><ref name=2009MNRAS.399L.118C/><ref name=2011ApJ...731...40C/>
==Name== The name "Galaxy X" was coined in 2011 in analogy to [[Planet X]].<ref name=PopSci-2011-01-13>{{cite journal |url= http://www.popsci.com/technology/article/2011-01/galaxy-x-invisible-satellite-galaxy-dominated-dark-matter-could-be-lurking-milky-ways-edge |title= 'Galaxy X,' an Invisible Satellite Made of Dark Matter, Could be Lurking at the Milky Way's Edge |author= Clay Dillow |date= 13 January 2011 |publisher= [[Popular Science]] }}</ref> <ref name=NBC-2011-01-13>{{cite news |url= http://cosmiclog.nbcnews.com/_news/2011/01/13/5831930-astronomers-search-for-galaxy-x |title= Astronomers search for 'Galaxy X' |date= 13 January 2011 |author= Alan Boyle |work= Cosmic Log |publisher = NBC News }}</ref>
==Controversy== In November 2015, a group led by P. Pietrukowicz published a paper arguing against the existence of Galaxy X. These authors argued that the four stars were not actually Cepheid variable stars and that their distances might be very different than claimed in the discovery paper of Chakrabarti et al. On this basis, the authors stated that "there is no evidence for a background dwarf galaxy".<ref name=Pietrukowicz-2015/> However the galaxy is still regarded to exist by others, with the stars being examined to be actual Cepheids.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4k5lCWKNvZg |title= The Dark Mystery of Galaxy X |author= SciShow Space |date= 5 July 2016 }}</ref>
