'''Western Canadian Select''' is one of North America's largest heavy crude oil streams.{{Sfn|Platts|2012}} It is a heavy blended [[crude oil]], composed mostly of [[bitumen]] blended with sweet synthetic and [[Natural-gas condensate|condensate]] diluents and 25{{Sfn|Mohr|2014}} existing streams of both conventional and unconventional{{Sfn|Mohr|2014}}{{Sfn|TMX/Shorcan Energy Brokers}} Alberta heavy crude oils at the large [[Husky Energy]] terminal in [[Hardisty, Alberta|Hardisty]], [[Alberta]].{{sfn|CAPP|2013}} Western Canadian Select—which is the [[Benchmark (crude oil)|benchmark]] for emerging heavy, high TAN (acidic) crudes—{{sfn|Argus|2012}}{{Sfn|Natural Resources Canada, GC|2011}}{{rp|9}} is one of many [[petroleum product]]s from the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]] [[oil sands]]. WCS was launched in December 2004 as a new heavy oil stream by EnCana (now [[Cenovus]]), [[Canadian Natural Resources|Canadian Natural Resources Limited]], Petro-Canada (now [[Suncor]]) and [[Talisman Energy|Talisman Energy Inc.]] (now [[Repsol]] Oil & Gas Canada Inc.).{{Sfn|CME Group|2012}}{{sfn|CAPP|2013}}{{sfn|Argus|2012}}{{sfn|Suncor|2013|1}}{{sfn|Cenovus|2010}} Husky Energy has managed WCS terminal operations since 2004{{Sfn|Husky Energy|2002-2015}} and joined the WCS Founders in 2015.{{sfn|Argus|2012}}
Crude prices are typically quoted at a particular location. Unless stated otherwise, the price of WCS is quoted at Hardisty and the price of West Texas Intermediate (WTI) is quoted at Cushing, Oklahoma.{{Sfn|Financial Post, Calgary Herald|2015a}} By December 14, 2015 with the price of WTI at $35 a barrel, WCS fell "75 per cent to $21.82," the lowest in seven years and Mexico's Maya heavy crude was down "73 per cent in 18 months to $27.74.<ref name="calgaryherald_dec_2015_">{{cite web | url=http://calgaryherald.com/business/energy/some-western-canadian-oil-selling-for-less-than-22-per-barrel | title=Some western Canadian oil selling for less than $22 per barrel | work=Bloomberg News via Calgary Herald | date=14 December 2015 | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> By February 2016 WTI had dropped to US$29.85 and WCS was US$14.10 with a differential of $15.75.<ref name="calgaryherald_feb_3_2016_">{{cite web | title=Commodities | work=Calgary Herald | date=3 February 2016 | accessdate=3 February 2016 |page=C7}}</ref> By June 2016 WTI was priced at US$46.09, Brent at MYMEX was US$47.39 and WCS was US$33.94 with a differential of US$12.15.<ref name="calgaryherald_June_17_2016_">{{cite web | title=Commodities | work=Calgary Herald | date=17 June 2016 | accessdate=17 June 2016 |page=B6-B7}}</ref> By December 10, 2016 WTI had risen to US$51.46 and WCS was US$36.11 with a differential of $15.35.<ref name="calgaryherald_dec_10_2016_">{{cite web | title=Commodities | work=Calgary Herald | date=10 December 2016 |accessdate=10 December 2016|page=C9}}</ref> According to monthly data provided by the U.S. [[Energy Information Administration]] (EIA), in 2015 "Canada remained the largest exporter of total petroleum to the United States exporting 3,789 thousand bpd in September and 3,401 thousand bpd in October." This has increased from 3,026 thousand bpd in September 2014.<ref name="EIA_2016">{{cite report |url=http://www.eia.gov/petroleum/imports/companylevel/ |title=Petroleum imports |date=December 2016 |work=EIA}}</ref> This represents 99% of Canada's oil exports and gives Americans no incentive to pay more for Canadian petroleum.<ref name="Bloomberg_WCS_cheapest">{{citation |title=Canada’s challenge is how to make money selling the world’s cheapest oil — but it can be done |work=Financial Post |accessdate=26 January 2016 |first=Claudia |last=Cattaneo | date= 16 December 2015 |url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/energy/canadas-challenge-is-how-to-make-money-selling-the-worlds-cheapest-oil-but-it-can-be-done?__lsa=e1a0-e5f6}}</ref>
Bitumen comprises all of Canada's [[unconventional oil]], and is either upgraded to [[Synthetic crude|synthetic light crude]], processed into asphalt or blended with other crudes and refined into products such as diesel, gasoline and jet fuel oil.{{sfn|TD|2013}}
{{clear left}}
==Major producers== [[File:The Bow in Calgary.jpg|thumb|left|Cenovus headquarters, Calgary]] WCS was launched in December 2004 as a new heavy oil stream by [[Cenovus]] (then EnCana), [[Canadian Natural Resources|Canadian Natural Resources Limited]], [[Suncor]] (then Petro-Canada) and [[Talisman Energy|Talisman Energy Inc.]]{{Sfn|CME Group|2012}}{{sfn|CAPP|2013}}{{sfn|Argus|2012}}{{sfn|Suncor|2013|1}}{{sfn|Cenovus|2010}} [[File:PetroCanadaCenter.JPG|thumb|right|Suncor Energy headquarters, Calgary]]
Since it came onstream WCS has been blended at the Husky Hardisty terminal.{{sfn|Argus|2012}}[[File:Wcp 01.jpg|thumb|right|Husky headquarters in Calgary. Husky has been blending WCS since 2004]]{{Sfn|Husky Energy|2002-2015}}{{sfn|Argus|2012}} According to Argus, in 2012 the WCS blend is produced by only the four companies mentioned above. "[T]he prospects for adding new producers are complicated by the internal rules set in place to compensate each producer for its contributions to the blend."{{sfn|Argus|2012}}
Companies tied to WCS as benchmark such as MEG Energy Corp, whose output is bitumen, benefit with an annual cash flow increase of 40% with every $5 increase in the price of WCS.{{Sfn|Jones|2015}} Crude from MEG's 210,000-barrel-a-day Christina Lake oil sands site is marketed as Access Western Blend, which competes with WCS. Others such as BlackPearl Resources Inc. and Northern Blizzard Resources Inc also benefit from the higher WCS price. "In the seven weeks that heavy crude has staged its rebound, MEG shares are up 27 per cent, BlackPearl’s 37 per cent and Northern Blizzard’s 21 per cent."{{Sfn|Jones|2015}}
According to a report by real estate consultants [[Avison Young]], by August 2015 in downtown Calgary, "layoffs by major oil and gas companies" were reflected in higher vacancy rates in the second quarter.<ref name="ghost towers">{{cite web | url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/energy/ghost-vacancies-haunt-downtown-calgary-as-oil-patch-layoffs-empty-office-buildings?__lsa=c940-0dbd | title=‘Ghost vacancies’ haunt downtown Calgary as oil patch layoffs empty office buildings | publisher=Financial Post | date=12 August 2015 | accessdate=9 September 2015 | author=Geoffrey Morgan}}</ref>
==Historical pricing WCS== By 18 March 2015 the price of benchmark crude oils, WTI had dropped to $US43.34/bbl.{{Sfn|Financial Post, Calgary Herald|2015a}}{{rp|D6-D7}} from a high in June 2014 with WTI priced above US$107/bbl and Brent above US$115/bbl.{{Sfn|Krishnan|2014}}{{Sfn|Petroleum Services Association of Canada|2014}} WCS, a bitumen-derived crude, is a heavy crude that is similar to Californian heavy crudes, Mexico's Maya crude or Venezuelan heavy crude oils.{{Sfn|Foran|2013}} On 15 March 2015 the differential between WTI and WCS was US$13.8. Western Canadian Select was among the cheapest crude oils in the world{{Sfn|Tobben|Murtaugh|2014}} with a price of US$29.54/bbl on 15 March 2015,{{Sfn|Financial Post, Calgary Herald|2015a}}{{Sfn|Ewart|2015}}{{rp|C6-7}} its lowest price since April 2009. By mid-April 2015 WCS had risen almost fifty percent to trade at $US44.94.<ref name="Healing_2015_04">{{citation |title=Canadian oil and gas firms 'bleeding money' amidst darkest outlook in a decade |first1=Dan |last1=Healing |first2=Jeremy |last2=Van Loon |work=Calgary Herald |date=17 April 2015 |accessdate=17 April 2015 |url=http://calgaryherald.com/business/energy/energy-sector-earnings-outlook-darkest-in-a-decade }}</ref> By 2 June 2015 the differential between WTI and WCS was US$7.8, the lowest it had ever been.{{Sfn|Calgary Herald|2015a}} By 12 August 2015 the WCS price dropped to $23.31 and the WTI/WCS differential had risen to $19.75,{{Sfn|Financial Post, Calgary Herald|2015d}} the lowest price in nine years when BP temporarily shut down its [[Whiting, Indiana]] refinery for two weeks,<ref name="DOE_whiting" /> the sixth largest refinery in the United States,<ref name="largest_refinery">{{cite web | url=http://oilpro.com/post/17464/shutdown-largest-refinery-us-midwest-sends-regional-gas-prices-so | title=William Fletcher posted 23 hours ago K A Shutdown At The Largest Refinery In The U.S. Midwest Sends Regional Gas Prices Soaring | publisher=OilPro | date=12 August 2015 | accessdate=12 August 2015 | author=William Fletcher}}</ref> to repair the largest crude distillation unit at its Whiting, Indiana refinery.<ref name="DOE_whiting">{{cite web | url=https://www.oe.netl.doe.gov/docs/eads/ead082515.pdf | title=Update: BP Restarts CDU at Its 413,500 b/d Whiting | publisher=U. S. Department of Energy: Office of Electricity and Energy Reliability | date=25 August 2015 | accessdate=9 September 2015 | author=Energy Assurance Daily}}</ref> At the same time Enbridge was forced to shut down Line 55 Spearhead pipeline and Line 59 Flanagan South pipeline in Missouri because of a crude oil leak.<ref name="largest_refinery" /><ref name="shutdowns">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/oilsands-companies-feel-the-pain-as-canadian-oil-price-falls-1.3188430 | title=Oilsands companies feel the pain as Canadian oil price falls Alberta companies at break-even point or losing money | publisher=CBC | date=12 August 2015 | accessdate=12 August 2015 | author=Kyle Bakx}}</ref> By December 2015 the price of WCS was US$23.46, the lowest price since December 2008<ref name="oilsandsmagazine">{{citation |url=http://www.oilsandsmagazine.com/western-canadian-select-wcs-historical-pricing/|title=Western Canadian Select Historical Pricing |date=12 December 2012 |work=Oil Sands Magazine}}</ref> and The WTI-WCS differential was US$13.65.<ref name="FP_2015_10_12">{{cite news |title=Commodities | publisher=Financial Post, Calgary Herald | accessdate= |date=10 December 2015 | pages=B7}}</ref> By June 2016 the price of WCS was US$33.94.<ref name="calgaryherald_June_17_2016_"/>
In mid-December 2015, when the price of both Brent and WTI was about $35 a barrel and WCS was $21.82, Mexico's comparable heavy sour crude, Maya was also down "73 per cent in 18 months to $27.74. However, the Mexican government had somewhat protected its economy.<ref name="calgaryherald_dec_2015_"/>
{{quote|"Mexico’s government insulated itself from the oil slump after it managed to hedge 212 million barrels of planned exports for 2016, using options contracts to secure an average price of $49 a barrel. The nation’s 2015 oil hedge provided it with a bonus of $6.3 billion."|Bloomberg News via Calgary Herald}}
== Characteristics == "The extremely viscous oil contained in oil sands deposits is commonly referred to as bitumen" ([[CAS Registry Number|CAS]] 8052-42-4) At the Husky Hardisty terminal, Western Canadian Select is blended from sweet synthetic and condensate diluents from 25 existing Canadian heavy conventional and unconventional bitumen crude oils.{{sfn|Cenovus|2010}}{{sfn|Argus|2012}}{{Sfn|Mohr|2014}}{{Sfn|TMX/Shorcan Energy Brokers}}{{Sfn|Cenovus|2013}}
Western Canadian Select is a heavy crude oil with an [[API gravity]] level of between 19 and 22 (API),{{sfn|Platts|2012}}{{sfn|Platts|2013}} 20.5° (Natural Gas and Petroleum Products 2009).{{sfn|NRC|2013}}{{rp|9}}
Western Canadian Select's characteristics are described as follows: [[List of crude oil products|Gravity]], Density (kg/m3) 930.1,{{Sfn|Cenovus|2010}} MCR (Wt%) 9.6,{{sfn|Cenovus|2010}} Sulphur (Wt%) 2.8-3.5%,{{sfn|Platts|2013}} TAN (Total Acid number) of (Mg KOH/g) 0.93.{{sfn|Cenovus|2010}}
Refiners in North America consider a crude with a TAN value greater than 1.0 as "high-TAN". A refinery must be retrofitted in order to handle high TAN crudes. Thus, a high TAN crude is limited in terms of the refineries in North America that are able to process it. For this reason, the TAN value of WCS is consistently maintained under 1.0 through blending with light, sweet crudes and condensate. Certain other bitumen blends, such as Access Western Blend and Seal Heavy Blend, have higher TAN values and are considered high TAN.{{Sfn|Crude Monitor}}
WCS has an API gravity of 19-22.{{sfn|Platts|2013}}
"Oil sands crude oil does not flow naturally in pipelines because it is too dense. A diluent is normally blended with the oil sands bitumen to allow it to flow in pipelines. For the purpose of meeting pipeline viscosity and density specifications, oil sands bitumen is blended with either synthetic crude oil (synbit) and/or condensate ([[Dilbit]])."{{sfn|NRC|2013}}{{rp|9}} WCS may be referred to as a syndilbit, since it may contain both synbit and dilbit.<ref name="Alberta_Energy2011">{{citation |url=http://www.energy.alberta.ca/OilSands/pdfs/CAREGlossary.pdf |format=PDF |title=Cost Analysis and Reporting Enhancement - Glossary of Terms |work=Alberta Energy |date=4 May 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2014 }}</ref>{{rp|16}}
In a study commissioned by the [[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State (DOS)]], regarding the Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) for the [[Keystone XL pipeline]] project, the DOS assumes "that the average crude oil flowing through the pipeline would consist of about 50% Western Canadian Select (dilbit) and 50% Suncor Synthetic A (SCO)."{{sfn|Lattanzio|2013}}{{rp|9}}
The Canadian Society of Unconventional Resources (CSUR) identifies four types of oil: conventional oil, tight oil, oil shale and heavy oil{{Sfn|Canadian Society of Unconventional Resources|nd}}{{rp|2}} like WCS.
== Volumes ==
By September 2014 Canada was exporting 3,026 thousand bpd to the United States. This increased to its peak of 3,789 thousand bpd in September, 2015 and 3,401 thousand bpd in October, 2015. This represents 99% of Canadian petroleum exports."<ref name="EIA_2016" /><ref name="Bloomberg_WCS_cheapest" /> Threshold volumes of WCS in 2010 were only approximately 250,000 barrels per day.{{sfn|Cenovus|2010}}
A devastating [[2016 Fort McMurray wildfire|wildfire]] that began on May 1, 2016, swept through [[Fort McMurray]] and resulted in the largest wildfire evacuation in [[History of Alberta|Albertan history]].<ref name="Global85%Stands">{{cite news|last1=Ramsay |first1=Caley |last2=Shum |first2=David |date=May 9, 2016 |title='Ocean of fire' destroys 2,400 structures but 85% of Fort McMurray still stands |trans-title= |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2688553/notley-in-fort-mcmurray-monday-to-survey-wildfire-damage/ |website=Global News |access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name="largestAB">{{cite news|url=http://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/fort-mcmurray-wildfire-pushed-back-even-as-temperatures-climb|title=Thousands flee from Fort McMurray wildfire in the largest fire evacuation in Alberta's history|date=May 3, 2016|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|newspaper=[[Edmonton Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510222635/http://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/fort-mcmurray-wildfire-pushed-back-even-as-temperatures-climb|archive-date=May 10, 2016|dead-url=no|last1=Parsons|first1=Paige|accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref> As the fires progressed north of Fort McMurray "oil sands production companies operating near Fort McMurray either shut down completely or operated at reduced rates."<ref name="EIA_2016_06_8" /> By 8 June 2016, the U. S. Department of Energy estimated that "disruptions to oil production averaged about 0.8 million barrels per day (b/d) in May, with a daily peak of more than 1.1 million b/d. Although projects are slowly restarting as fires subside, it may take weeks for production to return to previous levels."<ref name="EIA_2016_06_8">{{citation |url=http://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.cfm?id=26572 |date=8 June 2016 |accessdate=17 June 2016 |title=Fires near Fort McMurray are reducing Canada’s oil sands production |work=U. S. Department of Energy }}</ref> The Fort McMurray fires did not significantly affect the price of WCS.<ref name="EIA_2016_06_8" />
"According to EIA's February Short-Term Energy Outlook, production of petroleum and other liquids in Canada, which totaled 4.5 million barrels per day (b/d) in 2015, is expected to average 4.6 million b/d in 2016 and 4.8 million b/d in 2017. This increase is driven by growth in oil sands production of about 300,000 b/d by the end of 2017, which is partially offset by a decline in conventional oil production."<ref name="EIA_2016_02_25">{{citation |url=http://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.cfm?id=25112 |date=25 February |accessdate=17 June 2016 |title=Canadian oil production expected to increase despite lower prices |work=U. S. Department of Energy }}</ref> The EIA claims that while oil sands projects may be operating at a loss, these projects are able to "withstand volatility in crude oil prices."<ref name="EIA_2016_02_25" /> It would cost more to shut a project down - from $500 million to $1 billion than to operate at a loss.<ref name="EIA_2016_02_25" />
